AttributesList.AttributeSetDescription: Is_the_study_related_to_cancer: boolean// does this record describe a study related to cancer. Cancer is a group of diseases characterised by uncontrolled growth and spread of abnormal cells in the body. This includes solid tumours e.g., breast, lung, prostate, colorectal, or heamatological cancers e.g., leukemia, lymphoma or myeloma. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "oncological outcomes", "tumour progression," or "neoplastic diseases". Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to cancer.

Is_the_study_related_to_cardiovascular impact: boolean// does this record describe a study related to cardiovascular impact. Cardiovascular impacts refers to  the effects of external or internal factors on the health, function, or disease outcomes of the heart and blood vessels. This may include heart attack, heart disease, myocardial infarction, stroke, ischemia, hypertension, atherosclerosis, vascular disorders, or cardiopulmonary effects.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "CVD", "cardiovascular risk," "atherosclerosis", "blood pressure," or "cardiac events." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to cardiovascular impacts.

Is_the_study_related_to_heart attack or myocardial infarction: boolean// does this record describe a study related to heart attack or myocardial infarction (MI). Heart attack or myocardial infarction is a medical condition that occurs when blood flow to a part of the heart muscle is blocked, leading to damage or death of heart tissue. This may include heart attacks, acute coronary syndrome (ACS), cardiac events, or ischemic heart disease when associated with sudden cardiac injury.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "AMI", "non-ST elevation MI (NSTEMI)," "STEMI", "coronary thrombosis," or "cardiac arrest." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to heart attack or myocardial infarction.

Is_the_study_related_to_stroke: boolean// does this record describe a study related to stroke. A stroke occurs when blood flow to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from receiving oxygen and nutrients. This may include ischemic strokes (due to a blockage), or haemorrhagic strokes (due to bleeding in or around the brain), transient ischemic attack ("mini-stroke"), or cerebrovascular accident (CVA).  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "neurological events", "brain ischemia," or "vascular brain injury." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to stroke.

Is_the_study_related_to_dermatological impact: boolean// does this record describe a study related to dermatological impact. Dermatological impact refers to the effects of internal or external factors on the skin, including diseases, disorders, injury and physiological responses which may affect skin integrity, appearance, function or sensation. This may include rashes, dermatitis, eczema, urticaria (hives), infections (bacterial, fungal, viral), UV radiation or sunburn, pigmentation disorders and dermatological symptoms e.g., dryness, itching, blisters, inflammation, lesions.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "skin lesions", "dermal reactions," "epidermal damage," or "cutaneous manifestations." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to dermatological impact.

Is_the_study_related_to_developmental impact: boolean// does this record describe a study related to developmental impact. Developmental impact refers to any influence that affects the physical, cognitive, emotional or social development of individuals, particularly during critical growth periods e.g., infancy, childhood, and adolescence. This may include child development, growth outcomes, neurodevelopment, developmental delays, learning outcomes, or early life exposure events.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "developmental outcomes," "cognitive impacts," "childhood adversity," or "early-life vulnerabilities." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to developmental impact.

Is_the_study_related_to_birth outcomes: boolean// does this record describe a study related to birth outcomes. Birth outcomes refer to the health status and physical characteristics of a newborn at birth, which reflect both prenatal development and maternal health. This may include reference to low birth weight, preterm birth, gestational age, neonatal mortality, stillbirth, fetal growth, or birth complications.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "adverse pregnancy outcomes," "perinatal outcomes," "infant health at birth." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to birth outcomes.

Is_the_study_related_to_Cognitive, Neurological, and Psychological Disorders: boolean// does this record describe a study related to cognitive, neurological, and psychological disorders. Cognitive, neurological, and psychological disorders refer to a broad group of conditions that affect the brain, nervous system, and mental functioning, including thinking, emotion regulation, behaviour, memory, and movement. These disorders can be developmental, acquired, or degenerative. This may include reference to specific disorders e.g., dementia, epilepsy, depression, autism, schizophrenia, anxiety disorders or bipolar disorder. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "mental illness," "brain disorder," "cognitive decline," "neurodevelopmental condition," or "pscyhosocial impairment." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnositics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to cognitive, neurological or psychological disorders.

Is_the_study_related_to_Pubertal timing: boolean// does this record describe a study related to pubertal timing. Pubertal timing refers to the age or developmental stage at which an individual beings and progresses through puberty, marked by biological, hormonal, and physical changes that lead to sexual maturity. It can be classified as early (precocious), late (delayed) or typical onset. This may include reference to age at menarche, pubertal onset, pubertal development, precocious puberty, delayed puberty, or hormonal milestones. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "sexual maturation," "adolescent development timing," or "early puberty." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to pubertal timing.

Is_the_study_related_to_Diabetes_obesity_and_overweight: boolean// does this record describe a study related to diabetes, obesity and overweight. Diabetes, obesity, and overweight are interrelated metabolic conditions characterised by disruption in blood sugar regulation, excess body fat accumulation, or abnormal weight gain, which increase the risk of cardiovascular disease, stroke, kidney dysfunction, and other chronic illnesses. This may include reference to diabetes, insulin resistance, hyperglycemia, obesity, overweight, high body mass index (BMI), body fat, or adiposity. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "metabolic syndrome," "weight gain," "glucose intolerance," "pre-diabetes," "nutritional transitions,"or "lifestyle-related illness." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to diabetes, obesity and overweight

Is_the_study_related_to_infectious_diseases: boolean// does this record describe a study related to infectious disease. Infectious diseases are disorders caused by pathogenic microorganisms e.g., bacteria, viruses, parasites and fungi. They can be transmitted directly or indirectly between humans, animals, or through environmental vectors. This may include reference to different pathogen types e.g., bacterial (e.g., tuberculosis, cholera), viral (e.g., COVID-19, influenza, HIV), parasitic (e.g., malaria, schistosomiasis), and fungal (e.g., histoplasmosis, candidiasis), modes of transmission e.g., person-to-person (e.g., respiratory droplets, sexual contact), vector-borne (e.g., mosquito, ticks), zoonotic (e.g., transmitted from animals) or environmental (e.g., contaminated water, soil or food). Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "disease transmission," "infection risk," or "epidemic patterns." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to infectious diseases.

Is_the_study_related_to_airborne_disease: boolean// does this record describe a study related to airborne disease. Airborne diseases are infections transmitted through the air via aerosols, droplets, or dust particles or spores, allowing pathogens to be inhaled and enter the respiratory system. This may include reference to different airborne diseases e.g., viral (e.g., influenza, COVID-19 (SARS-CoV-2), measles, varicella (chickenpz), respiratory synctial virus (RSV)), bacterial (e.g., tuberculosis (TB), pertussis (whooping cough), diptheria, meningococcal disease), fungal (e.g., histoplasmosis, coccidioidomycosis (Valley fever), aspergillosis), airborne transmission, respiratory infection, droplet or aerosol speed, indoor air quality, heating, ventillation and air conditioning (HVAC), urban density and transmission risk, climate and meterological influences, or air pollution and increased vulnerability to respiratory pathogens. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "respiratory disease outbreak," "pathogen in air," "aerosol-borne infection," or "transmissible via air." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to airborne diseases

Is_the_study_related_to_coccidioidomycosis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to coccidioidomycosis. Coccidioidomycosis or Valley fever is a fungal infection, primarily a respiratory illness, caused by the inhalation of airborne spores from the soil dwelling Coccidioides species, a fungi endemic to arid and semi-arid regions. This may include reference to Coccidioides immitis and Coccidioides posadasii, fungal spores (arthroconidia), fungal lung infection, soil-borne fungal disease.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "respiratory disease," "respiratory illness linked to dust exposure," "endemic fungal infection in desert regions," "climate-sensitive mycoses." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to coccidioidomycosis.

Is_the_study_related_to_influenza: boolean// does this record describe a study related to influenza. Influenza or flu is a contagious viral respiratory illness caused by influenza viruses. It spreads primarily through airborne droplets, aerosols, and direct contact with contaminated surfaces or individuals. This may include reference to Influenza A, Influenza B, H1N1, H3N2, avian influenza, swine flu, respiratory virus, viral pneumonia, influenza-like illness (ILI).  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "seasonal respiratory infection," "flu burden," "pandemic influenza," or "climate-sensitive viral transmission." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to influenza.

Is_the_study_related_to_meningitis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to meningitis. Meningitis is an inflammation of the meninges, the protective membrane covering the brain and spinal cord, and is commonly caused by viral, bacterial, or fungal infections. This may include reference to meningococcal disease, bacterial meningitis, viral meningitis.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "inflammation of the meninges," "meningeal infection," "brain infection," or "cerebrospinal infection." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to meningitis.

Is_the_study_related_to_tuberculosis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to tuberculosis (TB).Tuberculosis (TB) is a contagious bacterial disease caused by Mycobacterium tuberculosis, which predominantly affects the lungs. It is transmitted through airborne particles expelled when an infected person coughs, sneezes, or speaks. This may include reference to tuberculosis, TB, latent TB infection, active TB, pulmonary TB, extrapulmonary TB, "airborne mycobacterial infection," "sputum smear positive TB," or "TB control programs."  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "chronic cough with infections potential," "airborne bacterial transmission in dense housing," or  "poverty-associated respiratory disease." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to tuberculosis.

Is_the_study_related_to_foodborne_disease: boolean// does this record describe a study related to foodborne disease.  Foodborne disease or foodborne illness refers to infections or intoxications resulting from the ingestion of contaminated food or beverages. This may include reference to causative agents e.g., biological (e.g., bacteria (e.g., Salmonella, E. coli, Listeria), viruses (e.g., norovirus, hepatitis A), parasites (e.g., Giardia, Toxoplasma), chemical (e.g., pesticide residues, heavy metals, mycotoxins, food additives) and physical e.g., foreign objects (e.g., glass, metal, plastic), foodborne illness, food poisoning, enteric infection, contaminated food, gatrointestinal disease.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "bacteria-laden foodborne pathogens,"  or "diarrheal illness from contaminated produce," Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to foodborne disease.

Is_the_study_related_to_cholera: boolean// does this record describe a study related to cholera.  Cholera is an acute diarrheal disease caused by ingestion of food or water contaminated with the bacterium Vibrio cholera, primarily serogroups O1 and O139. This may include reference to cholera, Vibrio cholerae, cholera outbreak, acute water diarrhea, dehydration from infection.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "waterborne diarrheal disease," "fecal-oral transmission," "epidemic-prone enteric illness," or "poor water treatment." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to cholera.

Is_the_study_related_to_fascioliasis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to fascioliasis.  Fascioliasis is a parasitic disease caused by liver flukes of the genus Fasciola, primarily Fasciola hepatica and Fasciola gigantica. Humans become infected by ingesting infective larvae present on contaminated plants, vegetables or water. This may include reference to Fascioliasis, liver fluke infection, Fasciola hepatica, Fasciola gigantica, bile duct infection.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "rural parasitic disease," "food-related parastic disease," "foodborne parasitic infection," or "zoonotic trematodiasis." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Fascioliasis

Is_the_study_related_to_Listeriosis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Listeriosis.  Listeriosis is a bacterial infection caused by ingestion of food contaminated with Listeria monocytogenes and primarily affects pregnant individuals, older adults, newborns and immunocompromised popluations. This may include reference to Listeriosis, Listeria monocytogenes infection, invasive listeriosis and pregnancy-associated literiosis.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "cold-tolerant foodborne pathogen," "perinatal infection," or "bacterial contamination in refrigerated foods."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Listeriosis.

Is_the_study_related_to_Vibrioses: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Vibrioses.  Vibrioses are a group of bacterial infections caused by various species of the genus Vibrio, commonly found in warm marine environments. This may include reference to Vibrioses, Vibrio infections, Vibrio vulnificus, Vibrio parahaemolyticus, Vibrio alginolyticus, marine bacterial infection, seafood-associated illness, or necrotising soft tissue infection from seawater.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "raw oyster consumption and illness," "coastal wound infections," or "climate linked increase in marine pathogens."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Vibrioses.

Is_the_study_related_to_Vector_borne_diseases: boolean// does this record describe a study related to vector-borne diseases.  Vector-borne diseases are infections transmitted to humans or animals via blood-feeding arthropods, known as vectors, such as mosquitoes, ticks, fleas and sandflies. This may include reference to vector-borne disease, arthropod-borne disease, zoonotic vector transmission, specific vectors e.g., mosquitoes, ticks, fleas, sandflies, tsetse flies, blackflies, specific pathogens e.g., viruses (e.g., dengue, Zika, chikungunya, West Nile virus), parasites (e.g., malaria, leishmaniasis, Chagas disease) or bacteria (e.g., Lyme disease, plague, rickettsioses).  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "vector control," "expansion of vector habitats," or "temperature thresholds for transmission"  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to vector-borne diseases.

Is_the_study_related_to_flea-borne diseases: boolean// does this record describe a study related to flea-borne diseases.  Flea-borne diseases are zoonotic infections transmitted to humans via the bites of inflected fleas, most often from rodent or domestic animal reservoirs caused by bacteria or parasites. This may include reference to flea-borne disease, flea-transmitted infection, flea vector, murine typhus, plague, cat scratch fever, jigger flea, Xenopsylla cheopis, Ctenocephalides felis, rat flea. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "flea-borne risk", "plague risk in warming regions," or "temperature-driven flea proliferation."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to flea-borne diseases.

Is_the_study_related_to_plague: boolean// does this record describe a study related to plague.  Plague is a zoonotic bacterial disease caused by Yersinia pestis, primarily transmitted to humans via the bites of infected fleas from rodent hosts. It can also spread through direct contact with infected animals, or in rare cases, aerosolised droplets from human-to-human transmission. This may include reference to plague, bubonic plague, pneumonic plague, septicemic plague, Yersinia pestis, flea-borne plague, Xenopsylla cheopis, rat flea, rodent reservoir. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "plague emergence due to climate variability"or "flea infestation and temperature thresholds."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to plague.

Is_the_study_related_to_Fly_borne_diseases: boolean// does this record describe a study related to fly-borne diseases.  Fly-borne diseases are infections transmitted to humans through contact with flies, either mechanically (via contaminated body parts) or biologically (where the fly acts as a host or intermediate vector). This may include reference to fly-borne disease, fly-transmitted infection, mechanical vector, e.g., housefly (Musca domestica), tsetse fly (Glossina spp.), sandflies (Phlebotomus, Lutzomyia), blackflies (Simulium spp.), stable flies, blowflies, and flesh flies, or specific diseases e.g., leishmaniasis, trachoma, sleeping sickness, onchocerciasis, or myiasis.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "waste accumulation and fly breeding," "fly infestation and diarrheal outbreaks," "heat and insect vector abundance," or "vector control."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to fly-borne diseases.

Is_the_study_related_to_Leishmaniasis : boolean// does this record describe a study related to leishmaniasis.  Leishmaniasis is a vector-borne parasitic disease caused by protoza of the genus Leishmania transmitted to humans through the bite of infected female sandflies (Phlebotomus, or  Lutzomyia). This may include reference to leishmaniasis, cutaneous/mucocutaneous/visceral leishmaniasis, sandfly, Phlebotomus, Lutzomyia, canine leishmaniasis, rodent hosts.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "climate-driven vector spread," "leishminasis outbreaks," or "zoonotic disease."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to leishmaniasis.

Is_the_study_related_to_onchocerciasis_diseases: boolean// does this record describe a study related to onchocerciasis.  Onchocerciasis or river blindness, is a chronic parasitic disease caused by the filarial nematode Onchocerca volvulus, transmitted to humans through repeated bites of infected blackflies (Simulium species). It is a vector-borne neglected tropical disease. This may include reference to onchocerciasis, river blindness, onchocercal skin disease, onchocercal eye disease, Onchocerca volvulus, Simulium, blackfly, visual impairment, or dermatitis or chronic skin itching.  Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "vector-borne filarial disease," "blackfly habits and biting rates," or "neglected tropical diseases."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to onchocerciasis.

Is_the_study_related_to_trypanosomiasis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to trypanosomiasis.  Trypanosomiasis refers to infections caused by protozoan parasites of the genus Trypanosoma, transmitted to humans by insect vectors. It includes Human African Trypanosomiasis (HAT) or sleeping sickness, caused by Trypanosoma brucei spp. and transmitted by the tsetse fly (Glossina spp.) and American Trypanosomiasis or Chagas disease, caused by Trypanosoma cruzi and transmitted by triatomine bugs (kissing bugs). This may include reference to trypanosomiasis, sleeping sickness, African trypanosomiasis, trypanosoma brucei, gambiense HAT, rhodesience HAT, tsetse fly, or Glossina. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "vector-borne protozal infection" "fly infestation in rural forest zones," or "livestock and wildlife reservoirs of Trypanosoma brucei."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to trypanosomiasis.

Is_the_study_related_to_mosquito_borne_disease: boolean// does this record describe a study related to mosquito-borne disease.  Mosquito-borne diseases are infections transmitted to humans through the bite of infected mosquitoes. Diseases involve mosquito vectors and include viral, parasitic and bacterial pathogens. This may include reference to mosquito vectors e.g., Aedes aegypti, Aedes albopictus, Anopheles spp., Culex spp., diseases e.g., malaria (Plasmodium falciparum, vivax), dengue, zika virus, chikungunya, yellow fever, japanese encephalitis, West Nile virus, or filariasis (e.g., Wuchereria bancrofti). Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "mosquito vector density," "mosquito net and vaccine interventions," or "climate-driven changes in mosquito habitat."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to mosquito-borne disease.

Is_the_study_related_to_dengue: boolean// does this record describe a study related to dengue. Dengue is a mosquito-borne viral infection caused by the dengue virus (DENV) which is primarily transmitted to humans by the bite of infected Aedes aegypti  or Aedes albopictus mosquitos. This may include reference to dengue, dengue virus, DENV, or diseases e.g., dengue fever, severe dengue, dengue haemorrhagic fever (DHF), dengue shock syndrome (DSS), or vectors e.g., Aedes aegypti, Aedes albopictus. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "expansion of Aedes range due to warming," "arboviral disease outbreak," or "climate-driven increases in dengue incidence."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to dengue.

Is_the_study_related_to_malaria: boolean// does this record describe a study related to malaria. Malaria is a mosquito-borne parasitic disease caused by protoza of the genus Plasmodium, that is primarily transmitted to humans by the bite of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. This may include reference to malaria, Plasmodium falciparum, P. vivax, P. ovale, P. malariae, P. knowlesi, severe malaria, cerebral malaria, asymptomatic malaria, imported malaria, or vectors e.g., An. gambiae, An. arabiensis, An. funestus. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "anti-malarial resistance," "malaria-endemic regions," or "maleria elimination programmes."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to malaria.

Is_the_study_related_to_Rift_Valley_fever: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Rift Valley Fever. Rift Valley fever (RVF) is a mosquito-borne viral zoonosis caused by the Rift Valley fever virus (RVFV), a Phlebovirus in the family Phenuiviridae. This may include reference to Rift Valley fever, RVF, RVFV, Phlebovirus infections, haemorrhagic manifestations linked to RVFV, or vectors e.g., Aedes, Culex, and Anopheles species, or floodwater mosquitoes. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "arboviral haemorrhagic fever," "vector control after heavy rains" or "flood-related vector-borne risk."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Rift Valley fever.

Is_the_study_related_to_Ross_River_virus: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Ross River virus. Ross River virus (RRV) is a mosquito-borne alphavirus that causes epidemic polyarthritis, an infectious disease characterised by joint pain, fatigue and fever. This may include reference to Ross River virus, RRV, epidemic polyarthritis, alphavirus infection, Ross River fever, or vectors e.g., Aedes vigilax, Aedes camptorhynchus, Culex annulirostris. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "floodplain mosquito control," "post-rainfall mosquito outbreaks," "viral arthristis," or "climate variability and RRV transmission."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Ross River virus.

Is_the_study_related_to_viral_encephalitis: boolean// does this record describe a study related to viral encephalitis. Viral encephalitis refers to inflammation of the brain caused by viral infection. It may result from direct viral invasion or from immune-mediated post-viral responses. It can be endemic or epidemic, and transmitted through various routes, including mosquitoes, ticks, direct contact, respiratory droplets, or latent viral reactivation. This may include reference to viral encephalitis, arboviral encephalitis, brain inflammation. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "mosquito-borne neuroinvasive illness," "meningoencephalitis in outbreak settings," or "encephalopathy in viral infections."  Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to viral encephalitis.

Is_the_study_related_to_West_Nile_virus: boolean// does this record describe a study related to West Nile virus. West Nile virus (WNV) is a mosquito-borne flavivirus, maintained in a bird-mosquito-bird transmission cycle, primarily involving Culex species mosquitoes. This may include reference to West Nile virus, WNV infection, West Nile fever, West Nile neuroinvasive disease, WNV encephalitis, WNV meningitis, WNND, flaviviral encephalitis or vectors e.g., Culex pipiens, Culex quinquefasciatus, Culex tarsalis, or mosquito-borne flavivirus. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "bird-mosquito transmission" or "mosquito-borne encephalitis surveillance." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to West Nile virus.

Is_the_study_related_to_Yellow_fever: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Yellow fever. Yellow fever is a mosquito-borne vrial haemorrhagic disease caused by the Yellow fever virus (YFV), a member of the Flavivirus genus. This may include reference to Yellow fever, Yellow fever virus, YFV, viral haemorrhagic fever, flaviviral hepatitis, urban yellow fever, jungle yellow fever, or vectors e.g., Aedes aegypti, Haemagogus spp., Sabethes spp. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "arboviral outbreak" or "fever and jaundice." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Yellow fever.

Is_the_study_related_to_Zika_virus: boolean// does this record describe a study related to Zika virus. Zika virus (ZIKV) is a mosquito-borne flavivirus that is primarily transmitted by Aedes mosquitoes that can cause mild febrile illness in adults and serious congenital birth defects when contracted during pregnancy. This may include reference to Zika virus, ZIKV, Zika infection, Zika fever, congenital Zika syndrome, Zika-associated microcephaly, neurotropic arbovirus or vectors e.g., Aedes aegypti, Aedes albopictu, mosquito-borne flavivirus. Recognise broader or indirect references e.g., "travel-related Zika risk" or "fever, rash, and conjuctivitis in pregnancy." Include literature that discusses incidence, types, diagnostics, treatment, risk factors or policy responses related to Zika.
